natural problem: Let $p(x)$ be a cubic polynomial such that $p(-3) = 4,$ $p(-2) = 4,$ $p(4) = 4,$ and $p(5) = 16.$  Find $p(11).$
natural solution: Let $q(x) = p(x) - 4.$  Then $q(x)$ is a cubic polynomial, and $q(-3) = q(-2) = q(4) = 0,$ so \[q(x) = c(x + 3)(x + 2)(x - 4)\]for some constant $c.$  Also, $q(5) = 16 - 4 = 12,$ and \[q(5) = c(8)(7)(1),\]so $c = \frac{3}{14}.$  Hence, \[q(x) = \frac{3(x + 3)(x + 2)(x - 4)}{14}.\]In particular, \[q(11) = \frac{3 \cdot 14 \cdot 13 \cdot 7}{14} = 273,\]so $p(11) = 273 + 4 = \boxed{277}.$
